SQL Database Administrator
Primary Responsibilities:
Manage SQL Server databases through multiple product lifecycle environments, from development to mission-critical production systems;
Install, configure, and maintain database servers and processes, including monitoring of system health and performance, to ensure high levels of performance, availability, and security;
Ensure all database servers are backed up and perform disaster recovery testing;
Provide database recommendations and guidance for development of internal applications and management of third-party applications.
When performance issues arise, determine the most effective way to increase performance including hardware purchases, server configuration changes, or index/query changes, providing problem resolution in real time;
Troubleshoot SQL Server service outages as they occur, including after-hours and weekends;
Perform scheduled maintenance and support release deployment activities after hours;
Identify poorly-performing and resource-intensive queries and suggest ways to improve performance;
Design and manage indexes for existing applications, choosing when to add or remove indexes;
Share domain and technical expertise, providing technical mentorship and cross-training to other peers and team members;
Advise and assist developers with database design and performance tuning of queries;
Document the company’s database environment.

Requirements:
5+ years MS SQL Server Administration experience required;
Experience with High Availability (HA) and Disaster Recovery (DR) options for SQL Server including Availability Groups, preferably in a multi-datacenter environment;
Experience with Performance Tuning and Optimization (PTO), using native monitoring and troubleshooting tools;
Experience with migrating databases and instances to newer versions of SQL Server;
Experience developing SQL and Transact-SQL queries and database objects;
Experience with server and storage virtualization technologies;
Experience working with Windows server, including Active Directory;
Excellent written and verbal communication;
Flexible, team player with a “get-it-done” personality;
Ability to organize and plan work independently.
