A Day in the Life…
Working as a member of the Enterprise Solutions team, the Database Administrator (Level 2) oversees and is responsible for the design, development, maintenance and support of enterprise and application databases ensuring data integrity, integration of systems, high performance, high availability and recoverability.
As the Database Administrator, Level 2 you will:
Contributes to the development and maintenance of database standards based on industry leading practice, in order to ensure effective database creation and operation, and standard naming conventions in database development in order to ensure effective system maintenance and support;
Contributes to the creation and implementation of programming standards for database objects and standards for access and use of the database to ensure it is the central repository of information for the University;
Conducts regular code reviews to ensure all applicable policies, procedures and standards are adhered to ensuring consistency in all database development;
Implements effective control protocols for system access to all databases ensuring outside sources are not permitted to directly interact with the database;
Meets with relevant stakeholders to understand and develop user requirements and specifications for the creation or amendment/updating of databases;
Analyze, design and develop ETL (Extract, Transform & Load) processes to ensure effective database function and operation, database applications within defined specifications to meet user needs, and integrations between disparate applications to ensure effective information management and transfer;
Produces database diagrams for documentation to support the design process with end-users, as well as support ongoing maintenance and future updating;
Plan, estimate and schedule tasks assigned to meet deliverables and timelines, using effective project management standards, in order to facilitate timely work completion;
Designs database automation, where possible, to reduce manual data management efforts, and support timely execution of regular data management and transformation activities;
Performs regular database maintenance, performance monitoring, load testing and support activities in order to ensure ongoing system performance meets defined standards; maintain and test recovery plans and backup procedures based on industry best practices to protect access to important data and systems;
Responsible for capacity planning, which includes analyzing database activity and growth to understand proper space available for growth;
Work collaboratively with the Infrastructure team to ensure proper resources are available to the database and schedule upgrades as required to ensure the platform remains current;
Diagnose and troubleshoot database errors, providing solutions to issues identified;
Responsible for recommending, creating and maintaining archival databases and other auxiliary databases that will enhance the University’s access to information while ensuring consistency, accuracy and optimum performance;
Participate in the timely migration or replacement of IT systems before the University is adversely impacted by inadequate systems;
Manage the security and disaster recovery aspects of a database; ensure the creation of a secure environment for development, user acceptance quality assurance testing (QA) and production, ensuring the consistency of data objects between the environments;
Implement and support data governance as determined by the University policy and guidelines;
Provide SQL expertise to all members of Enterprise Solutions as applicable, including assisting with queries that are more complex and require greater understanding and experience of the database and its capabilities than generally understood;
Propose design recommendations and optimizations working with Business Analysts and application developers and others as a member of project teams to support project success;
Work with vendors in evaluating and implementing new technologies that must interface with enterprise systems;
Troubleshoot and resolve database problems using native and third party monitoring and troubleshooting tools;
Research, recommend and as approved, implement emerging database technologies that support a more stable, user friendly IT infrastructure;
All other related duties as required and/or assigned by the IT Manager, Applications Architect, or designate.
Irregular hours are required throughout the year to meet deadlines.
What you need to Succeed…
A bachelor’s degree in Computer Science or related field or equivalent experience;
Between four to ten years of experience in database development with SQL Server, MySQL or equivalent;
At least two years of experience coordinating and supporting IT business processes;
Ability to work remotely via reliable high-speed internet connectivity;
Skilled in SQL database management knowledge and skills, including design, development and maintenance of large/complex databases using leading software (e.g. MS SQL Server, MySQL);
Ability to monitor and tune database performance;
Ability to design backup and recovery strategies;
Knowledge of configuration and setup of database servers to support enterprise databases (Unix, Linux, Windows);
Understanding and knowledge of Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery planning;
Demonstrated ability for thorough and accurate programming and database work;
Demonstrated analysis and trouble shooting skills;
Understanding of full database development and maintenance life cycle;
Demonstrated ability to learn, understand and apply new technologies to the advantage of the University;
Ability to manage time and set priorities working with multiple users, tasks, projects and deadlines in a high-pressure environment;
One year to become fully familiar with University direction, policies, procedures and IT systems;
Provide clear, understandable written and oral documentation and presentations for recommendations, designs and solutions for a variety of technical and non-technical audiences;
Ability to negotiate solutions with clients throughout the University that can be effectively implemented;
Foster and develop an environment of teamwork and collaboration;
Ability to work both independently as well as in a team-oriented, collaborative environment;
Provide regular feedback, acknowledges success and the need for improvement;
Coach and mentor junior staff members in order to develop skills and confidence;
Fosters a climate of transparency, trust, and respect within the unit and in partnerships;
Strong situation assessment and problem-solving skills;
Ability to quickly evaluate options, make decisions and execute within an intense high-tech environment;
Strong investigation and analysis skills, able to assess issues across multiple software applications and platforms;
Able to decipher cryptic issues and create innovative solutions.
